##A girl in Wuhan: In panic forced to grow up, the future to learn to do housework learn cooking

Micro-signal. NBWEEKLY

Introduction of function, new media with temperature

It was clear to me that I wasn't growing as fast as my family was going through the crisis, and I began to re-examine my role in the family. I feel I should be a bridge between my parents and the world.
By Meng Yu, editor | Xiaodou format | Chen Xingmeng

After graduating from college in 2019, Li Xiangming, 22, has been living in Wuhan and worked for an accounting company near Houhu Lake in Jiang'an District, Wuhan. Having never left her parents, she had little to worry about in her life.

On New Year's Eve in 2019, Li Xiangming and his friends came to the party in the pedestrian street of Jianghan road. That day, she heard for the first time about "pneumonia of unknown cause" . There was no word at the time that the virus could be passed from person to person. It was not until January 18,2020,10 days after the family had a fever together, that Li's parents had another fever and Li began to panic. She began accompanying her parents to get shots, leaving at 2 a.m. to line up at the hospital and returning home at 5 p.m. the next day.

Since then, the mother's condition has worsened, but has been unable to do a nucleic acid test, and can not be hospitalized. And online news about pneumonia more and more, Li Xiangming's heart is more and more chaotic. Finally, on January 28, my mother went for a nucleic acid test, and a few days later, it was negative. Li Xiangming's hanging heart was finally put down. For a month, Li Xiangming had been forced to grow up in bewilderment.

Here is Li Xiangming's dictation:

One
The whole family had a fever and was in and out of the hospital

On January 8, my father, who was rarely ill, developed a fever. I drove him to the nearest Wuchang Hospital, where he received an anti-inflammatory shot, and he was fine, but for the next two days my mother and I began to have repeated low-grade fevers. We also went to Wuchang Hospital to get shots and get our fever down.

I mentioned to my parents on December 31 that I had seen "pneumonia of unknown cause" in Wuhan on Weibo, but I don't know what the disease is, what the symptoms are, and whether it is contagious or not. So, no thinking, no protection.

On January 17, my father had a fever again, and he prescribed some medicine at Wuhan People's Hospital. I felt something was wrong and began to worry faintly, was it pneumonia? The next day, my mother also had a fever and began to cough. I don't know if it's psychological or not, but I also feel a little bit sick in my throat at the same time that there's been an increase in news coverage of COVID-19. So they decided to go to the Wuhan Union Hospital for a chest CT..

My lungs showed normal, and my parents' CT Scans said, "consider infectious lesions. ". Mother's film shows, left lung a little infection, at that time I did not think about this, I am more worried about, will develop lung cancer, because the mother is physically not good.

(photo provided by interviewees)

That night, I sent my mother's film to a friend who worked in radiology at a hospital in Huangpi District, Wuhan, and asked him to look at it. He told me that the main reason for this was pneumonia, but he didn't mention COVID-19.

Since then, the number of people in the hospital has increased day by day. Every morning, I accompany my parents to the Union hospital injection. The line was so long that I couldn't get home until 5 p.m. the next day. Because my parents were sick, so I made them sit on the sidelines, and I stood in line. For a long time not to eat and drink, and interrupted the work and rest, we are really tired, but what can be done. Everywhere I looked, people were so tired, some of them just sat on the ground.
I accompanied my parents in the Concorde Hospital for three days injection, my father is completely well, can eat and drink, but my mother has not improved, still in the cough. On January 21, the mother had a second chest CT at Concorde Hospital, which showed that part of her right lung was also infected. The doctor told me orally, see the result of the film, mostly viral pneumonia, as for whether it is COVID-19, still have to be tested, now this is the best case in hospital, but the hospital has no beds, so first home isolation.

(photo provided by interviewees)

On January 23, some patients from the fever clinic were transferred to Wuhan Red Cross Hospital. The next day, I said I had a little breathing difficulties, my mother worried to death, very worried that I was infected, has been urging me to check.

It turned out that there was no infection, but my mother forbade me to follow her to get an injection. The whole family was very anxious that day. I wanted to get a hospital bed for my mother, and two major surgeries in August 2019. I'm afraid she won't make it. Running around like this every day, waiting in line for shots, it's torture. Second, I was afraid that if they heard what the doctor said, they would really think it was something.

My mother said more and more urgent, she was going to cry, finally said, if I go to the hospital today, then this disease she died, waiting at home. My whole family was silent for, like, three minutes, and I finally gave in and let them go.

Also on this day, the city of Wuhan was declared closed. Although it is to control the epidemic situation, but I am really very sad, why did Wuhan become like this?

Every day for the rest of my life, I disinfected my home and looked up a lot of information online. I Cook for my mom as the Tongji Healer told me. Actually, I don't Cook. I can't cook. I also took the risk to order chicken soup takeout, read the reviews of that takeout for a few days, people have been buying, I also bought, wait for my mother injection back to give her to drink. I am at home during the day, cut vegetables, do some housework, steam a bowl of egg soup, waiting for my parents back.

Two
Waiting for tests, Internet help

January 25, the mother cough has not improved, feel the lungs burn panic, she went to the Red Cross hospital examination, the results showed that both lung infection. I was frantic. I wanted to know if it was COVID-19. But every hospital my mother visited, including Wuchang, Wuhan People's Hospital, Union Hospital and Wuhan Red Cross Hospital, said they were not authorized to do the test.

(photo provided by interviewees)

I asked them how to get access? The doctor said we need a specialist. But they don't know where the experts are or how to find them. There was a rumor online that there weren't enough kits, so I asked if there weren't enough kits, and he said no, or that you needed an expert to apply for a test. Wanted to be hospitalized, and the hospital said there were no beds.

I really do not know what to do, the same day two tweets for help. Later, there is micro-blog staff said to help me authenticate, I gave each other information, after the certification caused a lot of attention. Internet users told me that there are many hospitals, I will call a hospital, five hospitals, seven hospitals, Hankou Hospital, Lung Hospital, People's Hospital of the Eastern Hospital of these six hospitals, asked whether to do nucleic acid test, said no.

Some netizens mentioned that they could first go to the Community Health Service Center for treatment. I immediately found the number from the Internet, contacted the community, the community staff did information registration, told me that the earliest tomorrow will have feedback. But he didn't give me a clear answer as to whether or not it would be possible to do a nucleic acid test.

After registering in the community, staff members come to inquire about the situation every day. I didn't know anything about it, and I thought, how could someone my parents'age be receiving so much information? I don't think the publicity is good enough. Wuhan, including the ban, is to contact the community to use the car. If I hadn't seen it, they probably wouldn't have found out until it was too late, which would have delayed their progress.

One of the most memorable moments for me was when I contacted my mother in the hospital bed in Wuchang. At that time, I got the hospital admission form, after the registration of the nurse, said to go to the head of the emergency department to sign, she raised her finger in a direction, I looked for half an hour to find no one. And then I asked a doctor, and he said you could just go ahead and register, and he'd let me know if there was a bed. I went back to the nurse, who said I had to get the chief's signature. As I was being pushed around, at a loss, I saw a couple of old people holding hands with each other. They were hunched over, walking slowly, just like us. The two of them ended up tearing up the sheet, saying they weren't going to read it, and they just left.

I feel really bad, I think, like them, how to do? But I have my hands full right now, and there are a lot of people like us who don't know what to do.
(community plays national anthem, residents shout "Go Wuhan" , Tuyuan Weibo)

On the evening of the 27th, our community spontaneously sang the national anthem on the balcony, many people shouted, Wuhan refueling. At that moment, my heart was bitter and moved, and I went out to shout a few words. I think, if we stick together, we can get through this.

Three
A false alarm, reflect on the growth

On January 28, my mother received a call from Concorde hospital saying that she could go for a nucleic acid test. Then the community called and said that if they were sure to register today, they could go to Wuchang Hospital for a nucleic acid test tomorrow. I felt a bit conflicted, I asked myself at the Wuchang Hospital on the 27th, and their answer was no clearance. But I didn't have time to think about it, in order to know the news as soon as possible, I registered my father's name in the community, and then told my mother to rush to Concord Hospital to do the test today.

After mom finished the test, the hospital said she could make an appointment for tomorrow's test, so she made an appointment for her father at the hospital. Later, the doctor told my mother that if she didn't get a call at night, she was fine. A few days later, my mom got a text that came back negative. She wore a mask and went into the living room to tell us the news. I am quite glad, holding a heart finally put down.

Since my father's symptoms had gone away after his first injection and seemed to have returned to normal, I wasn't too worried about my father, and my mother's nucleic acid test had come back, and I felt a little less tense. But the tests are still being done, and we're still waiting on the father's results.

I didn't tweet the diagnosis right away, not because I didn't want to share the good news, but because reading too much on social media can cause panic if you're not careful. Now I get a lot of private messages every day, and I read every single one of them. Some people are over-panic, said Ta's body temperature is now 37 degrees, is infected, how to do. Others, like me, have been in the hospital for days without a diagnosis.

To be honest, I'm just a supplicant, and all I can do is comfort them and share some of the dry stuff I've learned these days, like the Tongji University cure article. But then people kept asking, and I tweeted the day after the results came in.

For 22 years, this has been the worst month of my life. The first time I encountered such a big thing, I dare not cry in front of my parents, do not want to let them worry, on their own hide in the quilt at night crying. I used to go to bed at 10 o'clock every night on the dot, but this time I often lose sleep and have started taking tranquilizers. In fact, every time my parents go out to the hospital in the wee hours of the morning, I am awake. I would immediately get out of bed, put on a mask and walk into the living room, telling them to make sure they wore the surgical mask I bought, otherwise they could get cross-infection there.

I also know that my mom didn't really say anything to me, so she's probably more upset, and she doesn't know what to do. Once, I found her phone's search history filled with COVID-19 related content. We just don't want to worry each other.

This time, it was clear to me that I wasn't growing as fast as my family was going through the crisis. I was forced to grow up, and I began to re-examine my role in the family.

In the future, I have to learn to do housework and cooking, can not be like this, my mother is sick, wearing a mask and also to cook for me. And make sure my parents get in shape. Only a strong immune system, will not be easily knocked down by the virus.

Besides, I think I should be a bridge between my parents and the world. They are older and don't surf the Internet much, and Wechat is the most used mobile APP. Now is the network society, the information explosion state, if not actively to collect information, it is difficult to understand the latest situation. On the 27th, Wuhan began to implement community-based classified diagnosis and treatment. If it wasn't for what netizens told me in private messages and comments, I wouldn't know at all. Originally, the community could still register and arrange for medical treatment.

I think this micro-blog help somewhat played a role, at least more quickly from the network to hear more about the new situation. In fact, before I do not play a lot of micro-blog, but now to my mother also downloaded micro-blog, I helped her to follow a few health science type of bloggers, always can see a few things.

In the future, if I know something new, I will tell them in person, rather than the past to shake a link or message to the three of us in the group, whether they click on a closer look, I am not sure.

Now I'm eagerly looking forward to the end of the epidemic. I've never seen Wuhan like this before. The streets are empty, and the eyes are filled with people wearing masks.

If the outbreak is over, the last thing I want to do is take my parents for a walk. They had never left the city, and I wanted to go with them to see the beautiful Great World, Shanghai.
(at the request of the interviewee, Li was given an alias.)

What is the one thing you want to do after the outbreak?

Many of our plans have been delayed by the cold winter, and while we are at home, we are watching the epidemic every day, hoping to wake up with good news and get out of the house as soon as possible, do what you want to do the most during this time.

What's the first thing you want to do after the outbreak? Are you a meat eater? Or did you see him right away? Or maybe you figured out something, and you want to change it later?

I didn't tweet the diagnosis right away, not because I didn't want to share the good news, but because reading too much on social media can cause panic if you're not careful. Now I get a lot of private messages every day, and I read every single one of them. Some people are over-panic, said Ta's body temperature is now 37 degrees, is infected, how to do. Others, like me, have been in the hospital for days without a diagnosis.

To be honest, I'm just a supplicant, and all I can do is comfort them and share some of the dry stuff I've learned these days, like the Tongji University cure article. But then people kept asking, and I tweeted the day after the results came in.

For 22 years, this has been the worst month of my life. The first time I encountered such a big thing, I dare not cry in front of my parents, do not want to let them worry, on their own hide in the quilt at night crying. I used to go to bed at 10 o'clock every night on the dot, but this time I often lose sleep and have started taking tranquilizers. In fact, every time my parents go out to the hospital in the wee hours of the morning, I am awake. I would immediately get out of bed, put on a mask and walk into the living room, telling them to make sure they wore the surgical mask I bought, otherwise they could get cross-infection there.

I also know that my mom didn't really say anything to me, so she's probably more upset, and she doesn't know what to do. Once, I found her phone's search history filled with COVID-19 related content. We just don't want to worry each other.

This time, it was clear to me that I wasn't growing as fast as my family was going through the crisis. I was forced to grow up, and I began to re-examine my role in the family.

In the future, I have to learn to do housework and cooking, can not be like this, my mother is sick, wearing a mask and also to cook for me. And make sure my parents get in shape. Only a strong immune system, will not be easily knocked down by the virus.

Besides, I think I should be a bridge between my parents and the world. They are older and don't surf the Internet much, and Wechat is the most used mobile APP. Now is the network society, the information explosion state, if not actively to collect information, it is difficult to understand the latest situation. On the 27th, Wuhan began to implement community-based classified diagnosis and treatment. If it wasn't for what netizens told me in private messages and comments, I wouldn't know at all. Originally, the community could still register and arrange for medical treatment.

I think this micro-blog help somewhat played a role, at least more quickly from the network to hear more about the new situation. In fact, before I do not play a lot of micro-blog, but now to my mother also downloaded micro-blog, I helped her to follow a few health science type of bloggers, always can see a few things.

In the future, if I know something new, I will tell them in person, rather than the past to shake a link or message to the three of us in the group, whether they click on a closer look, I am not sure.

Now I'm eagerly looking forward to the end of the epidemic. I've never seen Wuhan like this before. The streets are empty, and the eyes are filled with people wearing masks.

On January 28, my mother received a call from Concorde hospital saying that she could go for a nucleic acid test. Then the community called and said that if they were sure to register today, they could go to Wuchang Hospital for a nucleic acid test tomorrow. I felt a bit conflicted, I asked myself at the Wuchang Hospital on the 27th, and their answer was no clearance. But I didn't have time to think about it, in order to know the news as soon as possible, I registered my father's name in the community, and then told my mother to rush to Concord Hospital to do the test today.

After mom finished the test, the hospital said she could make an appointment for tomorrow's test, so she made an appointment for her father at the hospital. Later, the doctor told my mother that if she didn't get a call at night, she was fine. A few days later, my mom got a text that came back negative. She wore a mask and went into the living room to tell us the news. I am quite glad, holding a heart finally put down.

Since my father's symptoms had gone away after his first injection and seemed to have returned to normal, I wasn't too worried about my father, and my mother's nucleic acid test had come back, and I felt a little less tense. But the tests are still being done, and we're still waiting on the father's results.
